hands_on_practices.problem:
A right-cylindrical, axisymmetric soil specimen is tested in triaxial compression under quasi-static conditions. The specimen has height $L$ and radius $r$. The current load step is executed under axial displacement control, enforcing a prescribed axial displacement increment $\Delta \bar{u}_{z}$ at the top boundary while maintaining constant confining pressure $\sigma_{3}$ along the lateral surface. The discretization reduces to a single dominant axial displacement degree of freedom $u_{z}$ and a scalar load-path parameter $\lambda_{p}$ that scales a uniform reference axial traction pattern applied on the top face. The constitutive behavior in this increment is represented by a constant axial tangent modulus $E_{t}$ (linearized response for the step). The quasi-static finite element equilibrium at the incremental level is linearized to produce the augmented equilibrium-control system
$$
\begin{pmatrix}
K  -f \\
c^{\top}  0
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
\Delta u \\
\Delta \lambda_{p}
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
0 \\
\Delta \bar{u}_{z}
\end{pmatrix},
$$
where $K$ is the scalar tangent stiffness associated with $u_{z}$, $f$ is the scalar amplitude of the equivalent nodal load vector for a unit reference axial traction, and $c^{\top}$ enforces the displacement control on the single axial degree of freedom (so $c^{\top}=1$). The tangent stiffness is related to the specimen geometry and modulus by $K = \dfrac{A E_{t}}{L}$, where $A = \pi r^{2}$ is the specimen cross-sectional area, and the load amplitude for a unit traction is $f = A$. The deviatoric stress $q$ for axisymmetric triaxial conditions is defined by $q = \sigma_{1} - \sigma_{3}$, and for the present step the confining pressure is held constant so $\Delta \sigma_{3} = 0$.

Given $L = 0.10~\text{m}$, $r = 0.025~\text{m}$, $E_{t} = 50 \times 10^{6}~\text{Pa}$, and a prescribed axial displacement increment $\Delta \bar{u}_{z} = 1.00 \times 10^{-4}~\text{m}$ (compression taken as positive), use the augmented system above to solve for $\Delta \lambda_{p}$ and $\Delta u$. Then compute the resulting deviatoric stress increment $\Delta q$. Express the final deviatoric stress increment in $\text{MPa}$ and round your answer to four significant figures. The final answer must be a single real number.
